{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516120","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516120"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:39:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:39:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12564"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12564"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.14,0.12,0.03,0.64]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5063"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111918"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5063"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12564"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93982"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"1453"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8461"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11123"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11745"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14000"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42782"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45659"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45688"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111918","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111918"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old Aboriginal man presents to the General Practice clinic for a check-up. He reports that he does not visit the doctor often. He has a history of hypertension and pre-diabetes recorded in previous medical visits. He does not take any regular medications. He currently smokes and is ambivalent about quitting. He does not know his family history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears generally well. His BMI is 29 kg/m\u00b2. His pulse rate is 80/min and regular, blood pressure 148/90 mmHg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal cholesterol: 6.5 mmol/L (3.0-5.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHDL: 0.9 mmol/L (0.7-1.9)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETriglycerides: 1.0 mmol/L (\u0026lt;2.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHbA1c: 6.2% (4.0-6.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther blood tests are within normal limits. After discussing his cardiovascular risk profile, the patient wants to commence medication to reduce his risk.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications is most appropriate to prescribe?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aspirin","Fenofibrate","Sitagliptin","Atenolol","Perindopril"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a 40-year-old Aboriginal man with multiple cardiovascular risk factors including hypertension, dyslipidaemia, smoking, and pre-diabetes (HbA1c 6.2%). Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples have a higher burden of cardiovascular disease and earlier onset compared to non-Indigenous Australians. Current guidelines recommend cardiovascular risk assessment from age 30 for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples (compared to age 45 for the general population).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerindopril\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate choice for this patient. ACE inhibitors like perindopril are first-line agents for hypertension management, particularly in patients with elevated cardiovascular risk. This patient has a blood pressure of 148/90 mmHg, which is above the recommended target of 130/80 mmHg for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples with additional risk factors. ACE inhibitors have been shown to reduce cardiovascular events and mortality in high-risk patients, even in those without established cardiovascular disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin\u003C/strong\u003E for primary prevention of cardiovascular disease is no longer routinely recommended due to the increased bleeding risk that may outweigh the cardiovascular benefits. Current guidelines suggest that aspirin should only be considered for primary prevention in selected high-risk individuals after careful assessment of bleeding risk, and generally not before age 50.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFenofibrate\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used to lower triglyceride levels, which are not elevated in this patient (1.0 mmol/L). While the patient does have dyslipidaemia with elevated total cholesterol, a statin would be the preferred lipid-lowering agent rather than fenofibrate. Fibrates have limited evidence for cardiovascular risk reduction compared to statins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESitagliptin\u003C/strong\u003E is a dipeptidyl peptidase-4 (DPP-4) inhibitor used in the management of type 2 diabetes. While this patient has pre-diabetes (HbA1c 6.2%), current guidelines recommend lifestyle modifications as first-line management for pre-diabetes rather than pharmacological therapy. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtenolol\u003C/strong\u003E, a beta-blocker, is not a first-line agent for uncomplicated hypertension according to current guidelines. Beta-blockers are generally reserved for specific indications such as heart failure, post-myocardial infarction, or when other antihypertensives are contraindicated. They have been shown to be less effective than other antihypertensive classes in reducing cardiovascular events, particularly stroke.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, perindopril addresses this patient\u0027s hypertension, which is a modifiable risk factor requiring immediate attention. A comprehensive approach would also include lifestyle modifications, consideration of statin therapy for dyslipidaemia, and smoking cessation support. Regular monitoring of his pre-diabetes (HbA1c 6.2%) would also be important.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples should be assessed for cardiovascular risk from age 30, with a lower threshold for initiating preventive therapy.","ACE inhibitors are first-line therapy for hypertension in patients with elevated cardiovascular risk.","Smoking cessation support should be offered at every opportunity, as it is one of the most effective interventions to reduce cardiovascular risk."],"references":["Commonwealth of Australia as represented by the Department of Health and Aged Care. Australian Guideline for assessing and managing cardiovascular disease risk. 2023. Available from: https://www.cvdcheck.org.au/overview"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93982"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12564"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93982","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93982"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-21T14:47:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-22T08:38:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5063"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111918"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type"